---- Comment ----
Comments are used to explain the code and are ignored by Python during execution.

Single-line comments
Placing am # symbol in front of the text you want to be a comment causes Python to ignore everything from that point until the end of the current line.
        # Single Line comment

Multi-Line CommentsPython does not have a dedicated syntax for multi-line comments (like /* ... */ in other languages). Developers typically handle this in two ways

        1 : Multiple Hashtags: The official recommended practice (per PEP 8) is to place a # at the start of each line.python# This is a              multi-line comment
                # that spans across
                # several lines.
        
        2 : Triple Quotes: You can use triple double quotes (""") or single quotes ('''). While technically string literals, Python                   ignores them if they are not assigned to a variable.
                """ This is also used as a
                    multi-line comment.
                """

Inline/code comments
The # symbol will cause Python to ignore everything from that point until the end of the current line, so inline comments can be created in this way.
x = 1 # assigns value of 1 to x
